	"conclusion": "For Intercom, the career page strongly precedes Linkedin: 83% of matched jobs (29/35) appeared on the career page first, with an average lead of 362 days (median: 379 days). An additional 130 jobs (79% of career-page listings) were never indexed by Linkedin at all. This confirms that the career page is the primary source of truth for job postings.",
	"geminiSummary": "Analysis of Intercom's job postings reveals a strong propensity for company career pages to publish roles significantly ahead of their appearance on LinkedIn. Of the 35 jobs matched across both platforms, 83% (29 jobs) first appeared on Intercom's career page. This lead averaged an impressive 362 days, with a median lead of 379 days, highlighting a substantial temporal advantage for the company's direct hiring portal. Only 4 jobs appeared first on LinkedIn, and 2 were posted on the same day.\n\nA closer examination of the lag distribution for the career page-first jobs offers nuanced insights for job seekers. While 5 jobs (17% of career page-first roles) provided an immediate advantage, appearing 1–3 days earlier on the career page, and 2 jobs were posted 31–60 days ahead, the vast majority—22 jobs (76%)—exhibited a lag of 90 days or more. This long-tail distribution, exemplified by top evidence jobs showing leads exceeding 500 days (e.g., \"Senior Product Designer\" with a +1001 day lag), suggests that many roles are either perpetually listed as evergreen positions on the career page, or experience exceptionally delayed syndication to LinkedIn.\n\nIt is crucial to note several caveats that may influence these findings. The analysis was based on a robust 200 career page snapshots but a significantly limited number of just 6 LinkedIn snapshots over the same analysis period (2024-01-01 to 2026-04-01). This sparse LinkedIn crawling coverage could potentially inflate the observed career page lead times and undercount instances where LinkedIn might have listed a job earlier or concurrently, as well as the 130 unique jobs found *only* on the career page. More frequent LinkedIn data collection would provide a more precise comparison.\n\nDespite these data collection limitations, the evidence consistently points to the career page as the primary, and often earliest, source for Intercom job postings. For job seekers, this implies a clear practical recommendation: consistently monitoring company career pages directly provides an undeniable advantage. While many roles exhibit very long lead times, indicating potential evergreen status, an immediate window of several days to weeks exists for a measurable subset of jobs, ensuring early access to newly posted opportunities that might not reach LinkedIn for extended periods, if at all.",
	"geminiAvailable": true
}